<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="402" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[113,646,1100,1703]" box="[113,258,1100,1126]" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[113,646,1100,1703]" lastBlockId="9.[676,1209,205,1095]" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">
Female (male unknown): idiosoma L/W 1250/ 1000, integument smooth, without sclerotized muscle attachments; L/W cx-1+2 375/210, cx- 3+4 500/330; ventral idiosoma: see 
<figureCitation box="[524,641,1229,1255]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[113,124,1686,1703]" captionTargetBox="[91,1224,282,1623]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[63,1263,144,1682]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 5. — Moramangabates pauliani n. gen., n. sp.; A, chelicera; B, palp in medial view; C, idiosoma, ventral view. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5402520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5402520/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">Figure 5C</figureCitation>
; caudal margin of cx-4 with a projecting, “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1842" box="[575,637,1260,1285]" class="Arachnida" family="Pionidae" genus="Piona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="402" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[575,637,1260,1285]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">Piona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- like” apodeme, but no sclerotized line extending from the base of this apodeme in the direction of the glandular opening on the coxa; legs (
<figureCitation box="[570,638,1357,1383]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[128,139,1686,1703]" captionTargetBox="[208,1116,210,1635]" captionTargetId="figure-14@11.[192,1130,201,1643]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 6. — Moramangabates pauliani n. gen., n. sp.; A, first leg; B, segments 4 and 5 of third leg; C, fourth leg. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5402522" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5402522/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) slender, bearing strong claws with well developed ventral clawlet and claw blades; all basal segments with stout, nail-like dorsal setae; long, stiff ventral setae arranged as follows: I-L-2 one distally, I-L-3 two centrally and two distally; I-L-4 three distally; II-L as I-L; III-L-2 two distally, III-L-3 two centrally, two distally; III-L-4 three distally (one of them slightly distanced from segment margin), III-L-5 two distally; IV- L-2 one distally, IV-L-3 three centrally, three distally; IV-L-4 three centrally, three distally; IV-L-5 three distally; furthermore rows of short- er, strong ventral setae on central leg segments increasing in thickness from I-L to IV-L; distal margin of I-L-5 with a fine whip-like seta, several further fine hairs and two strong ventral setae, distal margin of II/III-L-5 each with a curved, dorsally-directed, unilaterally pennate seta; all terminal segments with numerous, fine, ventral hairs, particularly dense on IV-L-6; leg measurements (segments 1-6, L/H): I-L 108/72, 157/76, 229/67, 302/58, 310/45, 260/49; II-L 100/72, 144/72, 225/67, 290/67, 302/50, 270/50; III-L 108/72, 148/72, 243/67, 329/38, 342/49, 333/49; IV-L 170/112, 189/76, 284/72, 360/58, 400/50, 387/50; genital plates each with 13 acetabula, L/W 210/140; gonopore L 520; excretory pore surrounded by a sclerite ring; gnathosoma L 450, W 160, with a long, distally enlarged and rounded caudal projection extending between the medial margins of the anterior coxal plate, but not fused to cx-1; chelicera basal segment L 300, H 100, claw L 145, with a ventrodistal series of very fine, smooth denticles (
<figureCitation box="[789,877,973,999]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[113,124,1686,1703]" captionTargetBox="[91,1224,282,1623]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[63,1263,144,1682]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 5. — Moramangabates pauliani n. gen., n. sp.; A, chelicera; B, palp in medial view; C, idiosoma, ventral view. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5402520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5402520/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
); palpus (
<figureCitation box="[987,1072,973,999]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[113,124,1686,1703]" captionTargetBox="[91,1224,282,1623]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[63,1263,144,1682]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 5. — Moramangabates pauliani n. gen., n. sp.; A, chelicera; B, palp in medial view; C, idiosoma, ventral view. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5402520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5402520/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
) with a distinct projection at distal end of ventral margin of P-2, and a central hump on P-3, both covered by fine, flat denticles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="402" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[676,1209,1132,1350]" box="[676,806,1132,1158]" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">DISCUSSION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[676,1209,1132,1350]" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">
The unusual setation of legs (lacking true swimming hairs, but with very long, hyaline stiff setae at distal margin of II-L-4, III-L-4/5 and IV-L-3-5) suggests that 
<taxonomicName authority="Gerecke, 2004" authorityName="Gerecke" authorityYear="2004" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Moramangabates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acari" pageId="9" pageNumber="402" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pauliani" status="n. gen., n. sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="402">Moramangabates pauliani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[784,951,1292,1318]" pageId="9" pageNumber="402" rank="species">n. gen., n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is adapted for life in stagnant waters.
</paragraph>
